Open plan living room and kitchen with views across London west facing. The whole flat is painted white and has a modernist refreshing style.

description:
A lovely, clean, quiet bedroom overlooking peaceful gardens in a spacious Victorian maisonette with stripped floor boards with a good-sized decked roof terrace, in a quiet Hackney street.

Hackney is in north-east London. It is 5.7 miles from my flat to Oxford Circus (regarded as the centre of London) which takes 20 minutes to get there from Hackney Central Station.

**If you don't know London, or Hackney, please check the map and make sure you are happy with the location before you book.**

The space
The bedroom you will stay in is clean, cosy and tidy with a desk and chair, a bedside table, a book case and wooden frame bed with comfortable mattress in a spacious traditional but stylish, clean and tidy Victorian maisonette with stripped floor boards and modern decoration with a good-sized decked roof terrace. The room is 9.6ft x 9.8ft/2.9m x 3m in size.

The maisonette apartment is set in the top floors of a house (divided into two
neighborhood_overview:
Hackney is full of independent cafes, bars, galleries, shops and markets. This East End area is international, dynamic, inventive and rich in history. It's also one of the greenest areas of London, with canals and rivers - kayaking and even horse-riding possible here.

We are near London Fields with the always popular Broadway Market on Saturday and also Chatsworth Road Market which takes place on Sunday.
It is three-minutes walk to Hackney Downs park, a large open green space. And a 10-minute walk to London Fields which is a great park with an outdoor heated swimming pool, tennis courts, great pubs, playgrounds. Walk through it and arrive at Broadway Market (Saturdays only), which is known for its organic food and vintage goods – a nice place to hang out for a coffee.

Just round the corner from the flat is Lower Clapton Road – full of useful food shops, cafes, general stores. And a few streets away is Chatsworth Road which is becoming a competitor to Broadway
host_about: Journalist, writer, and Hackney-dweller, I moved here from Notting Hill Gate in 2005 having been in west London for 17 years, and now wonder what took me so long to go east!

neighborhood_overview:
Mayfair is an area of central London, within the City of Westminster. Mayfair is roughly bordered by Hyde Park to the west, Oxford Street to the north, Piccadilly and Green Park to the south and Regent Street to the east. Most of the area was first developed between the mid 17th century and the mid 18th century as a fashionable residential district, by a number of landlords, the most important of them the Grosvenor family. The Rothschild family bought up large areas of Mayfair in the 19th century. The freehold of a large section of Mayfair also belongs to the Crown Estate (owned by the sovereign – at this time the queen). Mayfair is perfectly located for shopping and entertainment. Famous establishments include Savile Row, Burlington Arcade, the Ritz Hotel and the West End theatre district. New and Old Bond Street, known for fine jewellery, antiques and clothing is also nearby. This is also home to Sotheby's, one of Mayfair's oldest and most respected auction houses.

Mayfair

host_about:
I am an East Londoner, and, for the time being, a British Academy PostDoctoral Research Fellow at Queen Mary, University of London. I have finished my PhD in Applied Linguistics and Migration Studies not long ago and worked as a Consular Officer for the Italian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation in the past. I am currently developing a new research project, focused on investigating identity practices in long-standing and fast-changing multicultural societies. This project involves visits to the University of Washington, Seattle, and University of British Columbia, Vancouver. So I am technically based in three countries :)

I'm interested in cultural exchange, alternative music (especially grunge, stoner, punk rock, but also psychedelic stuff, oldies, and jazz). I love books and migration literature. I am a photography amateur, self-taught. You'll find some of my shots in the flat :). I have been training as a classic ballet dancer since I was able to walk, but I enthusiastically never made it become my career.
I absolutely love travelling, food, cinema and art. I've recently become vegan (have been vegetarian for about 20 years), but I'm still flexible at times... when it comes to cheese or sushi ;).

(Please note: I can understand French, but I unable to write & I can also understand Spanish if you don't talk too fast ;) )

Peace & Love,
Alex

4 tube lines; Circle, Hammersmith & City, District and Metropolitan line are 5 mins walk away. Direct tube to train stations; Euston, Liverpool street, Blackfriars, Kings Cross St Pancreas and Victoria.

neighborhood_overview:
Supporting an alternative scene within the heart of the city, this area often challenges established norms. Both classic and cutting edge, historical buildings like the Tower Hill, and avant-garde movements spearheaded by world-renowned museums like Whitechapel Art Gallery.
Brick lane is one of the trendiest streets with several graffiti tours along with clubs to various kinds of cuisines.
The historical Tower Bridge is only 14 mins walk from the flat.

The neighbourhood embodies struggle, survival, and success—its tumultuous past and endearingly sooty exterior cannot overshadow the achievements of its staid residents and unflinching creativity.
host_about:
Hi,
I am a warm and friendly host. I am happy to share the amazing secrets of London with you which I have accumulated while living here for 18 years. 

I am pleased to say that through Airbnb I have had excellent conversations and interactions with people from 29 different countries since I joined Airbnb in 2016. 
In June 2016, I travelled through France for almost a month and via Airbnb stayed in Private rooms in people's flat and was most impressed by the hosts and the hospitality. During that time I had put my entire flat on Airbnb.After coming back from France I started to put my spare room in my flat on Airbnb.

I love my flat. I have decorated it a bit like me, modern yet homely with a personal human touch. 

I am into meditation and energy and believe my flat has plenty of positive energy. I am learning modern dance and love the eclectic things that London provides from Wilton's music hall, Speak easy bars to vibrancy of Brick Lane street. 

I have worked in the banking sector and the charity sector and now run my own small business. 

I hope to host guests from all the countries that have Airbnb. 

I hope you enjoy staying at my place and I enjoy staying at yours. 

Until then, have a great day.

This area is an hidden gem only a short distance from Camden and Hampstead. It has some wonderful restaurants and pubs to choose from, we have craft breweries, specialist bakeries, independent coffee shops and cafes walking distance from the house.
We also have many choices of cinema from Odeon in Camden & Holloway to the Everyman in Hampstead and Muswell Hill.

host_about:
I'm a Londoner with a penchant for travelling far and wide. I'm a yogi, pilates instructor, jewellery designer, singer, skier, urban cyclist, software programme manager and curious about the world, the people & cultures that make up our global community. I love independent travel as it allows to you really spend time getting under the skin of places you visit. 
I find it hard to rate one country over the other as I've loved all the places I've ever visited. India captured my heart in a way others have yet to; the colours, the food, people and the sheer diversity of the country. I even loved the crazy roads. 
And as for city breaks, I would say that Berlin or Barcelona are in my top favourites, and a recent work trip to Iceland was amazing, and I'll definitely be returning soon.
What can't I live without? A pen and paper, a camera and a smile.

neighborhood_overview: Battersea is a wonderful part of London in which to stay, with Battersea Park just 10 minutes’ walk away, nice local neighbourhood restaurants (including the Michelin guide recommended Boqueria) and cafes, and all the attractions of central London just a short hop on public transport. There are multiple convenience stores and supermarkets along my road. Battersea Arts Centre, a leading arts venue, hosts an array of events in a beautiful building and has a really lovely cafe and bar (I recommend the burgers). I love walking through Battersea Park along the Thames river  and across the pretty bridges to Chelsea's Sloane Square and Kings Road. From my front door there's a clear view of the iconic art deco Battersea Power Station, which you may well recognise from the album cover for Pink Floyd's Animals and The Beatles' film Help!. The bars, restaurants and green space of Clapham are also within walking distance.

10 min tube to Oxford Street, Covent Garden, main theatres and museums.

The space

Bright, spacious, safe and comfortable place to stay in Central London, it is available to guests for long or short stays. The flat is professionally cleaned and we provide fresh cotton linen and towels.

The flat has one bathroom with tub and s
neighborhood_overview:
Head out to a trendy Upper Street wine bar, or stroll along Regent's Canal, only five minutes away. Angel is one of the most happening areas of lovely Islington and within walking distance of other cool areas, such as hip Shoreditch and Dalston.

The area is a mix of the modern and protected 17th, 18th and 19th Century buildings. If you like to shop or to eat out you will be spoilt for choice!

Angel Islington is full of fantastic bars, restaurants, coffee shops and green spaces. Upper Street and Essex Road are 2 minutes walk away and offer so many places to eat and drink. Canonbury Tavern is the best place for us to be. You can have a drink there or enjoy a locally sourced Sunday roast. Regent’s canal is about a 5-minute walk away from the flat, and The Narrow Boat pub is our favourite canalside pub, their sticky toffee pudding is unbeatable!

There is a traditional pub around the corner and a river running behind the house, the New River Walk. Very peace
host_about:
I am a published Italian novelist, software engineer and former archaeologist. I love art, collecting first editions of my favourite books and going to long walks. I worked at the British Museum, the Courtauld Gallery and the Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art. I am also an Airbnb Superhost, and I personally designed and furnished my home. You can find my passions around the apartment, and some of the literature prizes I won.
 
My co-host, Alberto, is a Director of Engineering and talented Creative Technologist. He was selected as one of the 100 top tech influencers in Europe for a few years. He has worked in the digital advertising industry and in startups for all of his career. Alberto enjoys everything tech, reading sci-fi novels, playing board games, hiking, and of course travelling. A self-proclaimed foodie, he loves baking and entertaining his guests with his latest creations.

Thanks for checking out our listings. Alberto and I hope we get the chance to welcome you to our home and to London. It's an amazing city with many different corners to explore.

As hosts, we want to help you make the most of your visit, whether simply by offering a comfortable place to stay or advice on things to do. We think it's nice to sample something of local life when travelling, and Airbnb is a great way to achieve that. We travel a lot and we always use Airbnb when abroad so we know that by experience!

After lots of experience hosting many international guests, we are now exploring other countries and cultures whilst guests continue to enjoy our beautiful home in London as we are away. We present our properties immaculately clean and are constantly improving and upgrading the facilities and amenities to make visits more comfortable and guest-friendly. Our aim is to provide a 'better than hotel' standard of accommodation for a more attractive price.

Medium-to-long-term accommodation in London is RARE and we are always booked quite far in advance - we recommend that you plan your trip early!

neighborhood_overview:
Stoke Newington is a vibrant and exciting place to be in London and luckily a place I call home. The flat is located directly next door to Abney Park cemetery, which is one of the Magnificent Seven cemeteries in London, the park is alive with birds and wildlife - you might even spot a flash of green parakeet from out of the window.
Nearby you will find Stoke Newington Church Street which is full of boutique shops, a diverse selection of restaurants to eat in and local nightlife can be found a short walk away.
The area is a mix of interesting spots to see and parks and green areas, in addition to Abney nature reserve next door a short walk or run and you will find Woodberry Nature Reserve, which has 2 reservoirs (which i often run) as well as Clissold Park, a large East London park which features its own herd of Roe Dear and 2 friendly goats.
Dalston and Shoreditch are also close by, a short 10 min bus ride will find you in one of London's most creative hubs.

Lewisham provides a a bustling, urban atmosphere. And Blackheath and Greenwich provide a wealth of culture, history and relaxing green open spaces.

Walk down the road and you have shops, supermarkets, a street market, restaurants, pubs, gym, pool, bus, train and DLR transport. Also a large Tesco supermarket open from 6am to midnight.
Walk to the top of the road for Blackheath Common a green open space that stretches to Greenwich Park and Blackheath village. Walk to Blackheath Village for great restaurants and pubs or walk over to Royal Greenwich Park; home to the Royal Observatory and the Meridian Line and GMT. If you have special dietary requirements or are vegan or just need health-food products there is a brilliant health-food shop and pharmacy (with lots of natural remedies) called Sheels at the bottom of the road.

Smack dab between Whitechapel, Docklands, Victoria Park and the Olympic Park, Mile End’s situation on the fringes means it has a little something for everyone.

Any nice pubs about?

Obviously: this is the East End. If you fancy something new, mixed with a dash of hipster cool, then try the recently refurbished Victoria on Grove Road. Elsewhere, popular spot The Crown offers a convenient location directly opposite Victoria Park. But if you’re looking for a real slice of old London charm, seek out the dusty delights of The Palm Tree, an unreconstructed boozer in the middle of Mile End Park that’s perfect for a warming drink and a singsong on a winter’s eve.

Living in Battersea and Nine Elms
Battersea is in the London Borough of Wandsworth and stands on the south bank of the River Thames, spanning from Fairfield in the
west to Queenstown in the east. The area is conveniently located just 3 miles from Charing Cross and easily accessible from most parts
of Central London.
The skyline is dominated by Battersea Power Station and its four distinctive chimneys, visible from both land and water, making it one
of London’s most famous landmarks. Battersea’s most famous attractions have been here for more than a century. The legendary
Battersea Dogs and Cats Home still finds new families for abandoned pets, and Battersea Park, which opened in 1858, guarantees a
wonderful day out.

being voted London’s second favourite shopping street. The SW11 Literary Festival sho

neighborhood_overview:
Located in the heart of London, Pimlico’s brick townhouses and white stucco facades hug its well-planned streets. The bowed windows of its cafes and taverns look across genteel scenes—Anglican churches, private homes, and pristine gardens capture Pimlico’s envied restraint. Underrated and often overlooked, Pimlico augments its refined culture with casual conveniences like farmer’s markets, and easy access to high-class institutions like Millbank’s Tate Britain museum.
It’s just ten minutes’ walk to Sloane Square, a stone’s throw from Tate Britain and Buckingham Palace is within easy reach. It’s also just a brisk half an hour walk to Trafalgar Square and, cutting through St James’s Park, the route is a scenic one too.

host_about:
Every time you leave home,
Another road takes you
Into a world you were never in.
 
New strangers on other paths await.
New places that have never seen you
Will startle a little at your entry.
Old places that know you well
Will pretend nothing
Changed since your last visit.
 
When you travel, you find yourself
Alone in a different way,
More attentive now
To the self you bring along,
Your more subtle eye watching
You abroad; and how what meets you
Touches that part of the heart
That lies low at home:
 
How you unexpectedly attune
To the timbre in some voice,
Opening in conversation
You want to take in
To where your longing
Has pressed hard enough
Inward, on some unsaid dark,
To create a crystal of insight
You could not have known
You needed
To illuminate
Your way.
 
When you travel,
A new silence
Goes with you,
And if you listen,
You will hear
What your heart would
Love to say.
 
A journey can become a sacred thing:
Make sure, before you go,
To take the time
To bless your going forth,
To free your heart of ballast
So that the compass of your soul
Might direct you toward
The territories of spirit
Where you will discover
More of your hidden life,
And the urgencies
That deserve to claim you.
 
May you travel in an awakened way,
Gathered wisely into your inner ground;
That you may not waste the invitations
Which wait along the way to transform you.
 
May you travel safely, arrive refreshed,
And live your time away to its fullest;
Return home more enriched, and free
To balance the gift of days which call you.
(For the Traveller, by John O'Donohue)

neighborhood_overview:
Aptly named, Angel is a hallowed spot of London life. Thought to be a prime spot for the urban elite, it combines trendy bars and restaurants with unique market stalls and vintage shops. Its diverse range of entertainment appeals to a wide range of clientele, from the stylish fashionista to the art-house film buff. And live music is always available somewhere nearby.
Stretching eastwards towards the uber-hip streets of Shoreditch, and all the way down Upper Street, Angel is an eclectic and vibrant area. Its Business Design Centre is always buzzing with consumer fairs, while Camden Passage enables you to slip away into a hidden gem of antique stores and charming cafes.
There’s a reason why Angel is one of London’s most beloved social hubs. neighborhood_overview:
There's plenty of heart in Hackney, where high art and edgy innovation meet. There are flavours to savour from its lip-smacking restaurants, not to mention world-class coffees (Square Mile coffee beans, anyone?). Quirky, scruffy, sleek or hip – the area's bars and pubs suit whatever taste you're packing, as do its diversions (you're seriously spoilt for things to do). And if money's still burning a hole, Hackney's shops and markets sell temptation by the truckload, from vintage fabrics and designer must-haves to rare meats and artisanal bread.

Eating: There's an exceptional range of places to eat in Hackney, from the famous Vietnamese and Turkish restaurants on Mare Street, to newcomers such as Lardo, which serves pizza and Italian dishes. Broadway Market is also lined with popular restaurants and bars, and its busy Saturday stalls sell organic produce and offer all the latest street food trends.

Kennington is excellently placed for some of the best cultural experiences in the Capital. It’s a mere 15 minute walk to the South Bank, the heartland of The Thames, and its theatres, galleries and concert venues, while the Tate Britain is within walking distance, too. Closer to home, The Riverside offers locals the chance to indulge on the river front, whilst a riverside walk showcases the current development taking place in Nine Elms.
Kennington is one of inner London's best kept secrets. It’s an enclave of brick houses and pretty squares containing some perfect examples of Georgian architecture. The most famous is the idyllic Cleaver Square, where locals play boules in the summer with merriment aided by the tiny Prince of Wales pub in the corner.

host_about:
Hi! Hello! Salut! Hola! Ciao! Ni Hao! Привет!

My name is Roman, before UK I used to live in US, Hungary, Slovakia and Ukraine.  I am an Engineer by education, Chef by passion and Entrepreneur by spirit.  I was engaged in a number of projects across different fields of interest, and I've lived in London since 2015.  Living here is very challenging but also very rewarding in many ways.  London is an amazing city and I want all the guests to experience the diverse beat and spirit that London has to offer. 

I enjoy traveling a lot but I enjoy hosting even more.  I like everything that is part of a peer-to-peer sharing economy.  Empty rooms, parked cars, unused tools, even dusty books, all of these can be made to work for other people and reward those whom it belongs to. 

So I'm helping people I know or have been recommended to in running their properties when they're away or busy with other things.  I enjoy engaging with travelers, answering questions, and providing some local info and advice. 

My other interests include cooking, hiking, kayaking, cycling and motorcycling, with lots of trips by foot, wheels and pedals already accomplished and many more to come.  Not to forget gardening and wild herbs and fungi foraging for my fusion recipes. 

I would be very happy to meet you in London and make sure that your stay is comfortable and enjoyable. 

Cheers!

host_about:
I work at a massive secondary school in London by day, make my own clothes by night and cycle all around the city in between. I have been in London for over 6 years now, but I'm originally from Budapest, Hungary.
Travelling is easy to get hooked on: discovering places for yourself, that you have read about or have seen a million times on pictures before, is what makes life worth living (among other things, of course...). I'm interested in getting a local feel of the destination, spending time doing what I would be doing on a fun filled weekend at home, like eating out, checking out a gig, watching a play, going to galleries, with a bit of sight seeing included for good measure!
I enjoy meeting people with a passion for something, who are spontaneous and make an effort to make their dreams come true, however big or little those might be.

Young creatives and trendsetters fill the fashionable clubs and bars that surround Shoreditch High Street, Great Eastern Street and Old Street. An eclectic dining scene features everything from trendy chain restaurants and smart gastropubs to artisan coffee shops and noodle bars. Vintage and design shops are plentiful.
host_about:
Hi! Hello! Salut! Hola! Ciao! Ni Hao! Привет!

My name is Roman, before UK I used to live in US, Hungary, Slovakia and Ukraine.  I am an Engineer by education, Chef by passion and Entrepreneur by spirit.  I was engaged in a number of projects across different fields of interest, and I've lived in London since 2015.  Living here is very challenging but also very rewarding in many ways.  London is an amazing city and I want all the guests to experience the diverse beat and spirit that London has to offer. 

I enjoy traveling a lot but I enjoy hosting even more.  I like everything that is part of a peer-to-peer sharing economy.  Empty rooms, parked cars, unused tools, even dusty books, all of these can be made to work for other people and reward those whom it belongs to. 

So I'm helping people I know or have been recommended to in running their properties when they're away or busy with other things.  I enjoy engaging with travelers, answering questions, and providing some local info and advice. 

My other interests include cooking, hiking, kayaking, cycling and motorcycling, with lots of trips by foot, wheels and pedals already accomplished and many more to come.  Not to forget gardening and wild herbs and fungi foraging for my fusion recipes. 

I would be very happy to meet you in London and make sure that your stay is comfortable and enjoyable. 

Cheers!

The district is frequently described as an urban village having a bohemian history, upmarket and home to some celebrities. Media reports often describe the area as “trendy”, “glamorous” and “swanky”.

neighborhood_overview:
Camden is one of London’s most iconic and distinctive areas. A huge player in the rock, punk and Britpop scenes of London’s last 40 years, this historic neighbourhood is known for being the stomping ground of many musicians, artists and writers. It’s not all about music, though: whether you’re looking for shopping, eating, or a great night out, Camden has it.Whether you’re a rocker, cool kid, metalhead, hippy, vintage queen or muso, you’ll find something to delight you in this fun part of North London!
The moment you step outside the tube station, Camden attacks the senses. Bass thumps from the market stalls' speakers, the scent of street food and incense permeates the air, and goths, punks, pushers and tourists shove past, giving the area an unorthodox charm. Camden Market has been one of the main draws of Camden for decades. Hi, this is my cute two bedroom apartment located in Hampstead garden suburbs (zone 3), just a 5 minute walk to the stunning Hampstead Heath!

Meadway Court is an imposing Grade II-listed complex built by Sutcliffe in 1913. It is set back from Meadway like a college quadrangle. The picturesque central courtyard contains two large lawn areas with substantial willow trees. The architecture has a collegiate or Tudor style with leaded lights, bay windows and a walkway above arched side colonnades.
neighborhood_overview:
Hampstead Garden Suburbs: The finest features of the Suburb are exemplified in this area. Grand houses rub shoulders with cottagestyle properties, closes exude charm, and all are a stone’s throw from the Hampstead Heath Extension.

Importantly, all the planning, and a great deal of the building, was completed before the Great War when putting the social and aesthetic aims of the Trust into practice was not prohibitively expensive. This was an ambitious project, bringing a country feel into the townscape, and making profits from the mansions, while creating numerous features that benefited all. Street trees, open spaces and the proximity to the Heath contribute to a leafy feel as do well maintained hedges and gardens. The curve of Hampstead Way and the open views across the Heath generates a more countrified atmosphere. neighborhood_overview:
Once an important part of London’s river trade, Bermondsey sat derelict for several decades, until the area’s wharves were renovated in the 1980s. Now it’s a lively part of town, with some exceptionally good restaurants and coffee houses, although they can sometimes be a bit tricky to find. Bermondsey also has plenty of excellent bars and pubs, usually packed to the brim with visitors and regulars. Bermondsey can turn Londoners into tourists: The Scoop in particular attracts both out-of-towners and locals to its free quality events.

If you haven’t already, make sure to take a stroll down Bermondsey Street to see what one of London’s most ancient streets has to offer. From the Bermondsey Street Festival to the Bermondsey Antiques Market, this street continues to thrive. I couldn’t recommend this area enough – and I'm not just saying that because it’s my home.

neighborhood_overview:
The north-west London neighbourhood of Kilburn stretches out on either side of Watling Street, the ancient Anglo-Saxon road that once connected pilgrims to Canterbury and St Albans. It is now known more prosaically as the A5 and marks the boundary of two London boroughs, Brent to the west and Camden to the east. Busy and bustling Kilburn High Road has a down-to-earth-character that continues to serve its long-standing Irish and Caribbean communities well. Famous residents have included supermodel Kate Moss, actor Hugh Laurie, and comedians galore.

Walk the back streets and Kilburn reveals its intriguing history and fine historic buildings. In the 12th century a priory was established close to what is now the junction of Kilburn High Road and Belsize Road. It was dissolved by Henry VIII but lives on in local street names Priory Road and Priory Terrace, where there are fine early Victorian stucco villas.

neighborhood_overview:
Nestled in a bend of the River Thames, with affluent Chelsea guarding its northern border, genteel Fulham is one of London's safe havens.
The Fulham of today is a firmly established upmarket location, packed with shops, bars, boutiques and restaurants. It's thoughtfully and spaciously laid out and a real delight for locals is the picturesque commute either along the river or through Eel Brook Common. Of course, there's the added bonus of plenty of lovely riverside pubs for a quick drink on the way home.

neighborhood_overview: The Boundary Estate is a housing development in Shoreditch, formally opened in 1900, in the East End and in East London, England. It is situated in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets. The estate, constructed from 1890, was one of the earliest social housing schemes built by a local government authority, although Liverpool Corporation had begun building tenement blocks in 1869. It replaced the Friars Mount rookery in the Old Nichol. It was built on top of the demolished rookery, the works were begun by the Metropolitan Board of Works in 1893 and completed by the recently formed London County Council. It was, arguably, the world's first council estate. Soil from the foundations was used to construct a mound in the middle of Arnold Circus at the centre of the development, surmounted by a still-extant bandstand. The estate consists of multi-story brick tenements radiating from the central circus, each of which bears the name of a location along the River Thames.

neighborhood_overview: Fashionable Notting Hill is one of London's most iconic neighbourhoods. Best known as host to the world’s second biggest carnival (after Rio’s Mardi Gras) and home to the famous Portobello Road Market, Notting Hill is also a serious destination for culture buffs and those on the hunt for a quintessential London experience. On weekends throughout the year, crowds stroll the two-mile stretch of Portobello Road Market. Colourful terraces are interspersed with antiques shops, buskers, historic pubs and clothing stalls. Straddling the antiques and fashion markets (which are busiest on Saturdays) are the equally old-fashioned and charming produce markets, the calls of fruit and veg sellers helping give the place a Dickensian air. There’s street food of all kinds, from paella and bratwurst to crepes and churros. The markets have a grungier feel past the Westway sports centre, but it is worth persevering for the people-watching and to admire the 100m-long Portobello Wall, which features public

This property has the best of both, right in-between Deptford and Greenwich.

“A place of great contrasts” fits Deptford perfectly. The lively high street — with a noisy, thrice-weekly market — and the artists’ enclaves.

A buzz has grown around Deptford in recent years, with the term ‘the new Peckham’ being thrown around frequently in reference to the relatively low rents, lively, creative community and urban cool atmosphere that can be found here. As always, the creatives have brought a series of hip restaurants, independent shops and cool coffee cafes with them, and as Peckham’s star rapidly begins to rise the developers are now coming in droves.

The heart of Deptford is its long high street, stretching from Deptford Broadway to Creek Road. There is a busy market on Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays selling everything from clothes to fish, fruit and vegetables.

neighborhood_overview:
Burnthwaite Road,  is ideally positioned just on the Chelsea/Fulham border and conveniently located for the shops and restaurants of the fashionable King's Road along with the fantastic transport links of Fulham Road.

But what you must know more about is Fulham. It is easily one of London's safe havens.

Sure, it began its journey in the 18th century as a hotbed of debauchery - but today, it stands as an upmarket location filled with shops, bars, boutiques and restaurants.

It's thoughtfully and spaciously laid out making it ideal for anyone looking for a beautiful surburban area to stay.

The attractive properties and kid friendly nature of the area has brought in a lot of families who then end up staying for years on end. Fulham is also known to have a large French and Italian community.

In terms of celebrities, it's worth noting that Harry Potter actor, Daniel Radcliffe, was born and raised in Fulham until the age of 12.

We do our best to always have someone to meet you at the apartment to hand over the keys and and offer advice and guidance about the local area. We like to keep the lines of communication open so my team and I are always a message or call away. When we're not busy with Property Management, we love to take some time out to enjoy this lovely city. Favourite places are the Royal Opera House and the Serpentine Lido in Hyde Park. We love to dance and seeing shows in the west end is one of the highlights for the team of being in London. We like to travel in style but are equally happy up a mountain or in the country as we are in the city. We love to get lost and explore new places by simply soaking up the atmosphere.

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

Bordering the beautiful Hyde Park, Bayswater is ultra-cosmopolitan, incredibly diverse and perfectly located for a short stay in London. And we’re not alone in thinking that, which is why Bayswater has the highest number of hotels than in any other London region.

Located in the City of Westminster, West London, Bayswater’s grand Georgian and Victorian buildings lend an imposing elegance to the area. Yet this timeless architecture gives way to some of London’s most fashionable shops, with Oxford Street, Bond Street and High Street Kensington just around the corner.

Bayswater is also home to an incredible choice of restaurants, with the aroma of food from every culture wafting through the evening air.

neighborhood_overview:
Shoreditch, It's a different place these days - smarter, slicker, much more monied - but it's still got that indefinable magic; it's still somehow, cool. It's no longer about drinking warm white wine out of plastic cups at a gallery – now Shoreditch drinking is all about supremely brilliant cocktails at some of London's best bars – some of the world's best bars, in fact. The pubs are excellent – authentic East End boozers with world-class drinks menus. And some of London's best restaurants, too – more inventive and creative than many of their central London counterparts, often in interesting, re-purposed venues.

Shoreditch was the playground of the Great Brit Artists of the Nineties. Jay Jopling's neighbourhood-defining White Cube may have decamped to Bermondsey, but the East End remains home to galleries, contemporary artists and makers essential to the capital's creative spirit. Two of the most interesting galleries are conveniently next door to each on Wharf Road: the alw
host_about:
Hi there, welcome to my home. I always enjoy to meet new people around the world and exchange stories, this always excites me when hosting my apartment. I’m happily to introduce you to the area, and tell you all about it why I fell in love with Shoreditch, if you planing to stay over and the weekends ,then you must pay a visit at the markets nearby. We have very unique markets with walking distance, that offers huge range of items such as jewellery, art, or mug and hat. I’m sure you will always find some unique piece that suits you. 

If you are here for a little city escape, my home will be just the perfect location for it. Brick lane, Liverpool Street, and all the best restaurant and bars are just few mins walk. Plus Hoxton station is just right behind the apartment. However, the easiest way I find, is the bus stop right across the road, and it would take you directly to Covent Garden, Tottenham Court Road, and Oxford Circus (15-30mins) If you still prefers underground, Old street station and Liverpool Street station are about 10 mins walk.

name: Home in Greater London · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 private bath
description:
The Artist's Studio is a completely refurbished and modernised artist's studio from the 1920's in the large garden of the main house in Greencroft Gardens. It has its own private garden and although only fifteen minutes from the centre of London it feels like being in the countryside. West Hampstead is a lovely part of town with lots of restaurants, cafes and pubs. Your hosts Stephen and Amanda are here to welcome you and make sure you enjoy your stay.

The space
The Studio was built in 1921 by the animal painter Edgar Fisher and he used it as his studio until the nineteen forties. His wife Beatrice was a child prodigy pianist and she had a grand piano in the studio. Their daughter Lillian, also a gifted singer, let out the studio after her father and mothers deaths and it was a much sought after space.
Stephen and Amanda came to rent the studio from Lillian in nineteen eight nine when they were students at The National Film School and knew Lillian as a fr
neighborhood_overview: South Hampstead is a very special part of London built in the mid to late nineteenth century on what had been open fields. It was designed with large private and communal gardens and the very distinctive, highly decorated, red brick. It is a very quiet and much sought after place to live with excellent transport links.
host_about: Stephen and partner Amanda bought the main house and Artist's Studio in 2002. In 2019 the Studio's refurbishment was completed and Stephen and Amanda decided to list it on Airbnb.  The Studio is full of paintings and light.  Stephen and Amanda are documentary filmmakers.  We hope you find us soon .
